The rough-looking cloud is cavitation caused by the water jet that precedes the bullet. It contains vortices moving so fast that their cores turn to vapor at low pressure, but all the bubbles are on the surface of a cylinder, with liquid water inside. The smooth cloud is supercavitation caused by the bullet pushing water outwardly as it advances, as in a shock wave. The inside is low-pressure water vapor. Creating this bubble takes a lot of energy, which comes from the kinetic energy of the bullet. Eventually, the low pressure inside the bubbles causes the water to return to the center. It bounces back because a very high pressure is created when the water collides with itself in the center. This is what destroys propellers that are run so fast that they produce cavitation.

If the pressure in front of the bullet were greater than behind it, the bullet would stop inside the barrel. It does not, so that means that the pressure in front is smaller than behind. Since the barrel behind the bullet does not burst from that pressure, neither does it from the pressure built-up in front of the bullet. Pressure in the barrel is greatest around the time when the bullet starts moving inside, and in that case it won't make any difference what's in front of the bullet.

Awesome video!  I don't believe the water is cavitating in the barrel, though.  Due to the hydraulic pressure induced by the projectile, the fluid is still in laminar flow much like the inside of an aerosol can.  Once the fluid reaches the end of the barrel (the nozzle), the water column trips into turbulent flow and either vaporizes and/or goes aerosol (a.k.a. cavitates)--Evident by the cloud starting in the flash suppressor and mushroom head coming out of the barrel first.  The Rayleigh-Plesset principle actually starts at the interface of those two pressure condition (hydraulic-to-ambient).  I wish there was an infra-red version of this video, because I would love to see the heat dissipation signature once the propellant gas and residue leave the barrel. I don't think Destin can invoke Bernoulli's principle as simply as he did in this video. It's not correct to say "faster moving fluids exert less pressure". The fluid flows you are comparing first have to start out at the same total pressure. A more precise statement of Bernoulli's equation is "the total pressure of a fluid (static pressure plus dynamic pressure) is constant along a streamline". These initial conditions for Bernoulli's equation are not satisfied in the case described here. An example of this is blowing a jet of air out of your mouth. This jet of air does not intrinsically have a lower static pressure than the surrounding (still) air because as you blew it out of your mouth you increased its total pressure. The two parcels of air you are trying to compare did not start at the same total pressure.

This is where my idea factors in. Feel free to give your thoughts as well. MY suggestion is that unburned gunpowder (the dark cloud) that exists the bore of the gun, while inside the "bubble" is compressed as the bubble collapses creating an ersatz chamber outside of the gun itself, actually.  As the unburned powder is compressed and consisting of sufficient heat and oxygen molecules to support combustion, the UNBURNED powder is then ignited causing the second flash. Think about it for a moment.  We always (?) see a large fireball upon detonation of the cartridge powder that occurs OUTSIDE the bore. That all is unburned powder still burning outside of the barrel which causes the flash. And the rebounding bubble as you point out bounces, if you will, through several cycles until the atmospheric conditions equalize. So there you have it. I don't think the gas from the piston cycles the weapon - it is just enough to unlock the bolt. The pressure inside the barrel is what does the main job. The same pressure that pushes the bullet forwards is what pushes now the empty shell from the cartridge and the bolt backwards. If the bolt is not locked the bolt would go back way to soon and a lot of the gasses and the energy will simply be lost. The reason we have those gas operated rifles is so we give maximum inertia to the bullet possible but not wait to much because if the bolt is unlocked too late then the gases will escape the barrel after the bullet has come out and there won't be any pressure left to cycle the bolt. That's why the position of the small hole on the barrel that takes small part of the gas pressure to unlock the bolt is so important - too close to the end of the barrel - you risk experiencing a jam, too close to the entrance - the bolt will unlock and the pressure will escape way too soon before the bullet gets is maximum speed.

Also, remember that pressure is very much directional.  It is simply an average force over an area... and the force in a liquid or gas can be directed so that more of the average motion of the particles are in a certain direction and hence the average force exerted is also higher in that direction.  In static equilibrium, pressure is essentially equal in all directions over a small surface area at the same depth.  But while flowing the pressure is generally only lower at the boundaries orthogonal to the flow.  The pressure is actually higher along and in the direction of the flow than against the boundaries of the flow (i.e. tube walls).  If the pressure were also lower in the direction of the flow, it would be lower than the water outside the barrel and so it would not escape the barrel, rather it would be pushed back further inside the barrel by the higher-pressure water outside!  But that's not what happens.  I mention this because like so many other subtle--but often repeated--incomplete ideas in science can spread misconception later on.

At the point of implosion when there is a flash of light (and Destin considers sonar luminescence), notice that the image of the muzzle (and the rest of the frame for that matter) jostles back and forth.  I would guess that about the same time it takes for the first bubble implosion is when the most energetic wave reaches the mirror box.  It would be no coincidence that the bubble oscillation would then be in phase with the waves reaching the mirror.  So Destin is likely correct that it is not sonar luminescence and likely a "reflection of the sunlight", but more specifically the change in apparent brightness is due to variation in angle of combined refraction/reflection through the mirror box.  If the camera were moved or the box manually vibrated, one might also see a change in the apparent brightness of the overall image.  The effect is just more pronounced when it occurs in sync with the bubbles.

The cavitation effect is taken into serious consideration when designing pumps for various purpose. The inlet of the pump lowers the pressure, and so if you're pumping very hot water from a boiler, for instance, you have to make sure you aren't lowering the pressure below the vapor point for the water, otherwise you get steam pockets (Cavitation) in your pump and... This video is awesome! Great work.  :D  I skimmed through the thread and didn't see it mentioned, so I thought I would drop a comment.  A lot of people look at bernoulli and lose sight of what it's saying - it really only applies to static systems in a gravity field.  You have either pressure head or potential energy, and if you stab a hole in the tank at the bottom he pressure is converted to kinetic energy.   I'm not sure if you did that in your explanation at the end but I though I would put up how I'm thinking about what's happening and you can decide for yourself.    The instant the shot is fired the front of the bullet will transfer the pressure from behind the bullet and the water bullet system will be pushed out of the barrel as a slug. The pressure in the water in this instant has to increase because it is accelerating and we are putting energy into the system.  As the liquid water hits the end of the barrel it will act to accelerate the body of water around it in a turbulent spray like mess that we see in the video.  The momentum imparted here is enough to overcome the pressure exerted by the atmosphere and a bubble starts to form of near vacuum water vapor behind it.  The bullet is ejected and travels through the liquid water immediately in front of it driven by the gasses from combustion behind it.  it travels through the near vacuum and the gasses from combustion fill the bubble.  The bullet hits the far site of the vacuum and it's momentum is transferred in an organized fashion from the leading edge of the bullet.     As the bullet slows the angle that the momentum extends away from the bullet changes from near perpendicular when the speed of the bullet was near the speed of sound in water to near straight ahead of it as it's speed is much slower than that of the speed of sound in water.  The corkscrew pattern is a consequence of the bullet having spin and not imparting it's momentum to the water uniformly.  As the pressure from the atmosphere slows and reverses the momentum imparted to the water from the bullet, the bubbles stop expanding and start collapsing.  There is very little area to close from the entry hole of the bullet into the second bubble it made, and there are very little gasses in this bubble beyond water vapor.  The first bubble collapses and compresses the combustion gasses which forms a spring the incoming boundary of water bounces off of.  The second bubble collapses to almost nothing because there are no gasses in there, and as you were saying is a sono-luminescence candidate - although I don't think it will because the spin of the bullet will make the boundary helical and have uneven pressures at the boundary which will promote water vapor going back to water liquid.  Love your channel.  Wanted to put this out there as bernoulli was all the rage for a while and it was fashionable to talk in those terms when it was in vogue but it gets applied to a lot of areas where it's a really ineffective way of thinking through the problem (Airplane wings.. looking at you...).  I thought you might be interested in walking through a process around conserving momentum.  Momentum is always conserved.  If energy is also conserved than Bernoulli's equation can be used to yield equivalent results in sometimes more convent metrics. Note, Navier stokes - the equations fluid mechanics is based on - is all based on conservation on momentum.

there would be some measurable factor regarding the bullet's properties as it speeds away: aerodynamic stability of the bullet. if the bullet is fired from a very stable barrel, i.e. a sniper rifle barrel, you'd suppose that the bullet's rotation is also very stable, but here we have an AK-47.  from the AK-47 here, though; it's very visible in that the bullet's rotation is perturbed by the viscous nature of the water through which it travels; it is perturbed in a way that amplifies rotations than simply spinning: if the bullet were to only spin with an axis parallell to its trajectory, then the bullet supposedly would go some distance further until the water slowed it down - this would be more dangerous to superheroes swimming underwater away from danger.   but because the bullet spins with more axes, than merely the axis parallell to its trajectory, it begins to "turn" in a way which deflects the water, by way of its own surface. as such, the bullet dissipates a lot more kinetic energy into the water (compared to traveled distance), and slows down very quickly indeed.  however, realistically, i'm not sure how "perfect" of a bullet spin that any current technology would be able to make, so don't get too excited. most mechanical engineering devices (especially those that are mass produced) are quite "imperfect"; even the more stable sniper barrels.

well, it's true that i found it hard to put this into words that would not confuse people; and i was very tired at the time of writing; so i simply called it by a term that i thought felt was descriptive of the phenomenon, yet not too inaccurate. first of all, i was thinking of it all from a bullet's own point of view as it travels, with direction of travel being somewhat vaguely defined.  tl;dr: i was trying to describe axial precession while tired, and all bullets do this to some degree. water as a medium for a bullet to travel through, affects motions like these much more than air, and so an imperfect motion like axial precession is heavily amplified vs distance travelled, compared to when bullets travel through air. a more "stable barrel", from my vague phrasing, would be able to create a "more perfect shot/bullet trajectory", although nothing is physically perfect. thus, a more "stable barrel" would be able to fire a round with less axial precession, thus allowing the round to travel further in any medium, though the effect would probably be easier to measure in an experiment like this underwater.  ### the barrel still simplified, the phenomenon i'm attempting to describe comes down to at least 3 factors having to do with the barrel, and from these came the term i called "stable barrel"; though these factors will affect one another, i think it best to consider them separately at first:  1: the rifling inside a barrel will aid in a bullet's trajectory's stability, making it turn around, spin. through angular momentum conservation, the bullet will remain spinning around until this motion's energy has dissipated (and it will also continue to travel forwards until its forward momentum has dissipated - the sum of these two are constitual terms going into the bullet's kinetic energy) - thus having transferred its kinetic energy to the air which it travels through, transferring kinetic energy to create turbulence and shock waves, as well as heat.  2: the weight of the barrel will give you an idea of how much the fired round's physical interaction has an effect to to even move the barrel itself; the blast from the round will shock the barrel, and the flowing of air, or pressure interactions, or simply the transfer of momentum could cause the barrel to move significantly in more than 1 degree of freedom (as described in classical mechanics) - simply because although explosions happen radial, they are not always perfectly so, and thus such explosions will affect the material they happen in proportionally. in any case, with a barrel, one would want to reduce a material's ability to distribute accumulated energy, so that such an energy outlet only happens in 1 degree of freedom.  in practice this factor means that for a stable shot, you'd want a barrel that is heavy enough compared to the bullet, that the round's explosiove energy goes into moving the barrel backward, and backwards only, thus limiting the degrees of freedom for any disturbance of other resulting motions. (as an addendum here, though, with a rifled barrel, you'll know from Newton's laws that because the bullet ends up with a rotary motion, then the rifle would have to rotate negative to the bullet's rotary direction: technically, yes, the rifle does - but from principles of momentum transfer, and because air is a mediating actor of this motion, the rotary effect on the rifle measurable, though negligible. if you still want to remain technical, though, then the number of degrees of freedom that you want to limit a barrel's energy transfer for, would be 2.)  3: minute imperfections in the material (not quantum or anything, but tiny and small): weight distribution in the alloy; surfaces that are not perfectly straight when considering microscopical scales; or even the rifling on the inside may have a minutely imperfect rotation progression. there will always be some level of imperfections in any fabricated material.  simply put, physics is about making sure that the energy that you put into a system, is neither wasted, nor polluting the result one is trying to achieve. Neil deGrasse Tyson had a much better phrase for how to say that, though, when he did a live show along Wil Wheaton, and interviewd Wheaton about his character in Eureka. point is, that you as a physicist, engineer, even designer or architect; you have to take into account all the ways that the end product might not be as perfect in practice, as all the nice formulas you've used in creation a design would lead you to think.  imperfections in any barrel, even small, will have their effects become visible on larger scales when you fire a round from it - this is in theory proportional to the amount of energy you release with the round, though as a perhaps comical extremal point, in practice this would be limited to the amount energy of a round's explosive force that would be strong enough to  tear a barrel apart; higher energies than that would be completely irrelevant to the experiment.  ### the bullet consider the bullet as an observer from the side, you are observing a bullet being fired. now also taking into account how all these imperfections might interact with the bullet's trajectory only from the barrel_, you should realize that _you are in no way guaranteed that the only kinetic energy constituents of the travelling bullet, come from the explosion's forward momentum transfer, as well as the angular momentum in the spinning direction that was intentionally induced by the rifling on the inside of the barrel: it might have a slight rotary motion along another axis.   the worst possible outcome for the bullet exiting the barrel and interacting with freely flowing air on the outside, would be if it the bullet was too small to begin with, and if its travel on the inside was so perturbed that the bullet had already begun pointing up/downwards or sideways upon the air-interaction at the outside. these conditions are unrealistic, so let's ignore that.  instead, looking at the bullet travelling, a much more relevant effect to take into consideration, is axial precession (there's a wikipedia article if you're curious, and though the article is centered on astronomical objects, the same motion is completely relevant to consider applied on smaller scales). such a rotary motion is usually a result of that the energy transfer from barrel's interaction with the bullet is not limited to 1 (technically, as explained above: 2) degrees of freedom.  but here's my point: if axial precession first begins to happen, then the tip of the bullet going sidewas will (first very slightly) begin to point in another direction than its travelling direction; up/down/sideways, and although this is just a very slight effect to begin with; as the bullet travels on, it passes through more of its medium (interacting with it as a wing on a plane does), and thus it turns more and more for every distance that the bullet travels, until the bullet ends up totally rotating the wrong way, much like the example that i wrote above, but ignored - the key difference having been how far the bullet was able to travel in total.  this is an effect that is completely visible effect in the underwater shots, here.

Inrevenant, the reason for the perturbation of the bullet's trajectory leading to the rotation in an axis, perpendicular to the initial vector is that in this video they use a 5.45mm AK-47, not 7.62mm. The first one has significantly lower initial energy. The bullet also has its center of mass slightly shifted backwards. When such a bullet enters the body it gains chaotic trajectory, which leads to greater internal damage, but it also has a lot less penetrating power. Firstly, it's not an AK-74. The AK-74 shoots a smaller bullet, the  5.45Ã—39mm. Awesome Video!!!  Some of my own observations and theories.  That Barrell really flexes underwater, I think the pressure to the piston, and the piston mechanism contribute to this.  Also, I think the column of water in front of the projectile is actually moving the piston, if not completely it is at least starting the movement early.  If you take the cyclic operation of the AK into consideration, the piston, rod, bolt all only move back a small bit under power from the piston, until the piston passes the holes you talked about letting the gas bubbles out.  That small bit unlocks the bolt.  Once unlocked, the bolt itself is pushed back by blowback of the round (like a standard automatic pistol). In this case, that blowback is much more than normal because of the increased chamber pressure due to the water in the barrel as you already discussed.  Again, this is all just my own theories. This bounce of the bubble, is a good visual of what happens when a Star runs out of Hydrogen, and goes Nova. While the star is burning, or fusing Hydrogen, pressure keeps the non-fusing layers above the core pushed out, but as soon as the Hydrogen is depleted enough to not support fusion, the core collapses leaving a bubble of very low pressure compared to what it was, an instant before. The outer layers, falling behind the core, collapses toward the center of the star, and when the pressure of all that mass falling into a small area, gets high enough, it stops the inertia, and bounces leading to the explosion we see as a Nova. Technically, it's neither.  The term "AK-47" is used in the United States to refer to basically any Kalashnikov variant that fires the 7.62 x 39 cartridge (the original AK-47 cartridge).  The rifle in the video looks like an Arsenal SLR 107-33.  It would be closer to an AKM, which is a "modernized" AK47 variant.  "AK-47" would correctly refer to a full-auto capable rifle without the modern upgrades which have become standard on the market.  So we could refer to this simply as an "AK-47" but in reality it technically would not be an AK-47 because it doesn't fire full-auto and it has upgrades.  The rifle in the video has some AK-74 pattern upgrades, such as the muzzle device and improved gas cylinder.  LONG story short, we can say "AK-47" to refer to any Kalashnikov that fires the 7.62 x 39 even though it's not technically correct.  An AK-74 variant fires the 5.45 x 39 round, which came later in response to the NATO 5.56mm round.  A quick and easy way to immediately tell is to look at the magazine.  A more dramatic, curved "banana" shape means it fires the 7.62 x 39 which would be an AK-47 variant.  A straighter-profile magazine means it fires the 5.45 x 39, which would be an AK-74 variant. Of course, that was "make believe", but this video actually validates that particular scene.  The short range that Bond had to shoot his enemy in that scene would have still made it a lethal hit. OTOH, this films shows that at more than a few yards, the bullet would not have even reached any sort of target.  In space, the range would be greatly extended. On the moon, it would still eventually fall to the surface--a .22 pistol could potentially have a range of several miles. But if someone were to shoot a gun in Earth or Solar orbit--unless that bullet hits the target being aim at at that moment, you'll have to worry for years or centuries later about who or what's going to eventually catch it--and it will be just as potentially lethal then as it was when fired!!

I have to correct you at 3:42. The rest of the cycle is not driven by inertia only. The small gas vents do not vent all the gas, it is just a means of managing excess pressure so the weapon doesn't over-cycle.
